        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The first spectral window is centered on the strong CH3OH 7_0 - 6_0 A transition at 338.409 GHz, the primary target of this study. By covering a total bandwidth of ~ 1 GHz, the entire 7_K - 6_K ladder is covered in this setting (the ladder goes from 338.1 to 338.8 GHz). Should the main line turn out to be exceptionally bright, indicating a lot of star-formation activity, the other lines will also be detected and provide constraints on the excitation conditions. 

SiO 8-7 is in the second spectral window. This shock tracer forms the secondary goal of this proposal, namely to ensure that any methanol emission is direcly linked to shock activity. 

Finally, the hot core tracer, methyl cyanide (CH3CN) is placed in the third spectral window. The 19-18 transition is a well-known and often-used hot core tracer. 

The channel width of all windows is ~ 2-3 km/s and is obtained by doing the maximum spectral averaging (x16). This width is enough to resolve any motion inside the cloud. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The requested angular resolution is 0.5", similar to the ALMA Cycle 2 observations of CO 2-1 observed toward the same regions (1.5 x 0.8"). This will allow for a direct comparison of these observations to the ones already obtained. 

The largest scales, as evidenced by the existing CO maps, is 3-5". There is no reason to believe methanol or any of the other tracers will be extended beyond the scales of CO, quite the contrary. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To estimate the sensitivity, Galactic high-mass clusters are placed at the distance of NGC 300, 2 Mpc. Most of the Galactic cores from the sample of Torstensson (2011) are at distances of 2 kpc, i.e. the geometrical dilution is 1e6. Typical cores have peak intensities of 100 Jy (15" beam) and emission is often spatially extended. When spatially and spectrally integrated, emission is of the order of 10,000 Jy km/s, i.e. 10 mJy km/s at a distance of 2 Mpc. Note that this is for a single high-mass cluster; typically molecular clouds host several sub-clusters, such as in Orion, and so this is a conservative lower estimate and where we place the 3sigma cut-off. 

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
