    <prp:abstract>Most stars in spiral galaxies form in their disks; yet due to sensitivity
constraints very little is known of the earliest, most embedded stages of star
formation in spiral galaxies outside the Milky Way. Recent continuum and
12CO observations of giant molecular clouds in the spiral
galaxy NGC 300 pave the way for characterizing these clouds more closely: are
they currently forming stars? 

One of the main signposts of current embedded star-formation activity is
molecular outflows. These are present during the embedded stages of star
formation an often light up in specific molecular tracers such as methanol and
SiO. We propose to use these well-known outflow tracers to probe a small sample
of giant molecular clouds in NGC 300 to address if they are currently forming a
population of embedded stars or not. Besides methanol and SiO, we will observe
methyl cyanide (CH3CN), a hot-core tracer, to search for additional signs of
star formation. Together, these will provide the first clear signs of embedded
star formation in the arms of a spiral galaxy and will pave the way for further
studies of embedded star formation using astrochemistry in extragalactic
regions.
</prp:abstract>
